<br>
But, having evolved throughout the various splendors of the world, it has become obvious that every moment I breathe, is another moment I will never breathe again. Ever. I will die. I will lose the only gift in my life, that is irreplacable. I understand that it is this very compassion for life that has forged such a strength for the death penalty, because people want to protect their loved ones, and themselves. <br>
<br>
Even though, the entire collective thought that you can take someone's life because they commited a crime of society isn't right. It isn't YOUR gift. Did the government give us life? Did the society at large conceive us? Of course the society provided us a shelter to become nurtured, and to live, but banishment and murder are not the same thing, and shouldn't be treated as such.<br>
<br>
If we are a society of peers, how can we judge each other? Moreso, while I agree what an atroscity murder is, who are we to judge what actions dictate enough to rob someone of life? And Meconan had a very good point, while you aren't teaching the inmate not to kill, you are in fact teaching the populace that if you kill, we kill. By that logic, what the government does is right, even if when the people do it, it's wrong. Even though we are a government of the people...<br>
<br>
Now I understand that I am not going to change the death penalty, and that all my post is, is conjecture and ramblings, but the simple fact is, is that because of our society's tendency to think if we can't see it, it must not be there, has allowed us to forego ethical principles to remain in territory that isn't ours to govern. You want to ostresize (dammit, sp?) someone? It's your country's right. You sheltered them, you didn't create them.<br>
<br>
Of course this is all moot anyway. If someone ever hurt my family members I would kill them, literally. As hypocritical as it is, I know I would bludgeon them to death with my own hands.<br>
<br>
Nekiah Dragonsbane<br>
Kyras Izgawd <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uasotus007.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Asotus007</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 219<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/12/01 9:44:09 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: way to go USA..</span><hr size=1> Many Americans are not comfortable being murderers. Understand, WE just killed a man. As a predominantly Christian nation ( 'vengence shall be mine', 'Thou shalt not kill', etc ) many Americans have a hard time justifying killing anyone for any reason as it is against our religion.<br>
<br>
 Others object for 'political' reasons. The high costs of State Sponsored Murder. The innocent people killed due to poverty and lack of adequate legal representation, etc.<br>
<br>
 Still others object for social reasons. We would rather identify ourselves with 'civilized' countries like most of Western Europe who don't kill their citizenry rather than the current company we keep on this issue ( China, Pakistan, et. al ).<br>
<br>
 Undeniably Mr. McVeigh commited a most grievous crime and should never be allowed to reenter society. Sometimes ya gotta 'thin the herd'. But please don't make the mistake of dismissing him as just a 'Crazy'. He was the product of the American Military. The date of the attack was not a coincidence, it was an anniversary. Killing him only lends his 'cause' a martyr and satisfied HIS wishes. We let him take the easy way out IMO. Maybe another 50 years hard time would have produced the 'Remorse' we soooo desperately seemed to want. As for the victims and their families, do you honestly think the got 'Closure' ( puke) from this ? No they did not. Closure is something that happens to an escrow. Killing this man did nothing to change the real loss felt by these people. Maybe a sense of revenge, but certainly not 'closure' in any real sense.<br>
<br>
 What troubles me is that in our cult of personality all we focus on is the monster ( mcVeigh ) and not the problem ( how we deal with our most violent criminals ). Christians are admonished to be 'Christ like'. Jesus never killed and willingly gave his own life rather than do so. If we profess to be 'civilized' &amp; 'christian', we need to stop making murderers out of ALL citizens and pursue other policy. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uraedwulf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Raedwulf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 113<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/12/01 9:53:58 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: way to go USA..</span><hr size=1> Wyvern:  The specifics of the death penalty (likelihood, time lag, appeals [unsuccessful 99% of the time]) are irrelevant to the lack of deterrence.  The only relevant factor according to the studies I've read, and there've been many, is that criminals don't think they'll get caught.  That's the same regardless of the success of the local constabulary.<br>
<br>
I cannot possibly fathom how you could justify killing the innocent (thereby creating many more victims), just to satisfy some bloodlust for the possibly guilty ones.  Especially when there is a perfect alternative in life imprisonment, which can possibly be used to rectify mistakes.  The news reported a man released from prison yesterday after 17 years, when it was conclusively presumed he wasn't guilty of a double homicide.  If his state had the death penalty when he'd been convicted, he'd be dead now, and we wouldn't have been able to fix that error.  Your option is unacceptable.<br>
<br>
<br>
Tullaian:  The sniper's death was necessary to protect other possible victims while he was still a threat.  McVeigh was no longer a threat.  And the criminally insane aren't release back into society after a verdict.  They go to an institution.  You won't live next to them.<br>
<br>
Timn:  Yes, it's the legal fees that ramp up the death penalty costs.  But should we eliminate those costs and possibly end up killing an innocent, just because it is costly?<br>
<br>
Smashgnome:  Although the media won't likely report it, there were two dozen injured victims and family members of the bombing that protested the execution.  They did not want more victims to be created, didn't agree that killing another was appropriate for their loss, or thought that letting him off this way was the easy way.<br>
<br>
Eraic:  There's no issue with &quot;trusting McVeigh&quot; if you stick him in jail for the rest of his life.  There's lots of states where they can stick you in jail, and you WILL NOT get out.  Period.  That's what I believe ought to be done instead of killing.<br>
<br>
Assilem:  Did you bother to check which of those 168 had their immediate family members speak out against the death penalty?<br>
<br>
Zephyris:  I haven't seen a single apathetic person post in this thread.  What the hell are you talking about?  Being against the death penalty is quite the opposite of being apathetic.  Those like me that have spoken against it, care very much about right and wrong.  I don't think it is right to kill someone simply because they are a killer.  That's not justice, it's simply revenge.<br>
<br>
You ought to try and get over your own prejudices and stereotypes, for it makes your arguments sound quite foolish.  I'm in favor of animal testing and environmentalist policies, against abortion and the death penalty.  Where are your foolish stereotypes now?<br>
<br>
Arnwolf:  Such a study has been done in Texas.  Violent crime is down 25% all over the country.  In Los Angeles, it's down even further, and the California use of the death penalty is more restricted and cumbersome than Texas.  When I said that it was accepted by Ashcroft (Bush's Attorney General), I wasn't just making it up.  Because your assumptions are in error, so are your conclusions. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uaoladariraveynfyre.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aoladari Raveynfyre</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/12/01 10:52:30 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Crypt</span><hr size=1> Everyone has a right to life until they take their own rights away by killing someone else... That defends my statement, Crypt.<br>
