<br>
While I do agree that there are some people who are just beyond hope, I did stay up and wait for 8am EST to note the passing of Tim McVeigh. He is in his most basic form, still a human being ... a life. I will not rant on the mishaps of European History and it's use of execution (thanks Inquisition!) in an attempt to point the finger elsewhere. But I will say this, McVeigh punished himself by carrying out the actions he did. No one else is to blame (he was found many times to be mentaly competent). <br>
<br>
There are few moments in American history where an entire nation can feel the pain of a few. In the recent past we've carried the pain of Colombine High School, the L.A. Riots, the murder of Nicole Brown Simpson and Ron Goldman, and far too many natural disasters to name. I do in fact remember how I felt when I watched the coverage of the bombing for the first time. And it only takes a moment of imagining yourself in the place of any one of those victims or survivors to realize exactly how horrid a crime this was. And sadly, how just the punishment was in return. <br>
<br>
Every death is a tragedy in someone's eyes. The Oklahoma bombing was a tragedy in everyone's eyes. It was unwarrented and undeserved. I know I would never want to watch my child picked out of some rubble. And I certainly would beg for 5 minutes alone with the person responsible. I'm not above those feelings. Do I agree in captial punishment as revenge? No. Do I agree with it as a form of punishment? Yes. A fine line but a distinct one none the less.<br>
<br>
I know American politics in some people's eyes may seem crude but this is indeed a case where the puishment fit the crime. He indeed was guilty, showed no remorse for his actions, and most would say only showed guilt when faced with failing appeals on his life. I will agree that not every case is as black and white as this one and there are innocent people in jail. Project Innocence is a wonderful organization, but their numbers are not astronomical. I know of about 7 or 8 released in my home state due to help from them. So yes, 8 people get a renewal on life, but within a week there will be 8 new murderers to take their cells. So I ask ... where do we draw the line?<br>
<br>
.....<br>
Jesus died for somebody's sins <br>
