<br>
I'm afraid that you are mistaken on quite a number of things.  &quot;they dont care what is right, but instead want their personal opinions enforced.&quot;  Isn't that the same as you?  Just because you are in the majority in the US, does this mean your position is right?  In 1776, the majority felt that slavery was right.  Were they correct?  Of course not.<br>
<br>
&quot;bleeding heart liberal mentality.&quot;  I'm sorry that you still don't get it.  I'm neither a &quot;bleeding heart&quot; nor a &quot;liberal,&quot; yet I'm against the death penalty.  Disagreeing with the majority is not being apathetic.  Your &quot;if a person&quot; intro is meaningless regarding your use of the term &quot;apathetic.&quot;  And as a number of those who have spoken out against the execution were family members of victims, your premise is contraindicated by the very matters you cite.<br>
<br>
If anyone disagrees with you, then they should be sent somewhere else?  I think you'll find yourself alone in a hurry.  Although many might agree with you on this point, there are bound to be other issues you won't agree with them on.  Even if you were a complete Tableau Raza (spelling?) and chose the &quot;majority&quot; opinion on every subject, you'd soon find yourself alone again, for everyone has views on some issue or another that aren't popular.  A few of the ones you've mentioned in this post would seem to put you in the minority.<br>
<br>
Again, I'm not suggesting that people convicted of &quot;capital crimes&quot; ought to be let out.  I think they ought to be locked up forever, or until we demonstrate that in fact, they weren't guilty.  We can't do that after an execution, can we?<br>
