<br>
Folks, there is wrong and then there is WRONG. Perhaps McVeigh was a product of his society or an opressive government. Perhaps he was in his mind a revolutionary. Fine. However, how many folks are rallying to the cry &quot;Remember Timmy!!&quot; ...? Granted, I am not listening for it, but pretty much everyone that I know personally looked up, nodded, and went back to what they were doing.<br>
<br>
For those of you who are uncomfortable with your ability to sit on a jury and vote to put someone to death; you would have been disqualified from McVeigh's jury for that very reason if you were honest during jury selection.<br>
<br>
McVeigh killed 168 people- he timed the blast to a point in time when he knew that the building was going to be occupied. It wasnt an accident, it wasn't anything but premeditated mass murder. He admitted he did it. I see no reason to spend any more of my or anyone else's tax dollars, effort, or energy to keep him alive so he can 'repent' or 'come to regret his actions'. I dont give a rat's ass if he ever does or does not. We washed our hands of his excerable existance and are now moving on. <br>
<br>
Sure, there are problems with the US judicial system; sure, there are problems with today's society both in the US and globally. Maybe the death penalty isnt a deterring factor. Again, I ask you- so what? Does the fact that the death penalty may not be a deterrent obviate the fact that McVeigh killed ONE HUNDRED AND SIXTY EIGHT human beings? Does the fact that killing McVeigh may not deter someone else from doing something similar in any way make the punishment less than appropriate?<br>
<br>
Finally, here is another question: Around 55 years ago, a group of people virtually eradicated a cultural group from the face of the earth. Their experiements and implements of death, terror, and destruction killed untold millions of people. Mass graves and concentration camps existed across Europe. While some of the people might have been 'just following orders', someone was giving those orders. Should one of those order givers-- one of the people who generated this abhorrent idea be allowed to 'ponder the mistakes of their past behaviour'? I am not trying to compare McVeigh to the Nazis, but seriously asking a question- At what point do you advocate the death penalty? Never? Only after killing more than say.... a thousand people? What about ONE person? What about war? Where do you say we should go to war? Never? At what point do you defend yourself or better yet- your child on the street? <br>
<br>
Sure, the death penalty is something that we dont want to have to use. I too would hate to see someone innocent be put to death. That certainly isnt the case here.<br>
