<br>
But you know what?  I, and again America as a whole, am willing to to accept those relatively innocent lives on our collective hands, in exchange for what happens as a whole.  And what you ask is that?  <br>
<br>
In the case of Japan, a bloody world war ended much sooner and with less loss of American life than would have been gained through conventional warfare.  And that is fine with me.  If the WWII Japanese, military and civilians alike, did not want to risk getting killed, they should not have attacked Pearl Harbor.  I am sure someone can put some spin on that, but fact is, we were at war, it was us against them, and Harry S Truman would have had one hell of a time explaining to my great grandmother why another one of her sons would have had to die storming some other crappy island hopping point on the way to Japan, like her firstborn son did on Iwo Jima, when the war could be ended by dropping 2 bombs with zero loss to American life.<br>
<br>
What happens in the case of the death penalty?  I am willing to take any odds you want to lay down that we have executed more guilty people than innocent ones in this country.  America as a whole, from state to state and under federal law, has agreed we are willing to chance killing an innocent person to keep the option of killing a guilty person available.  I count myself in that majority.  You apparently are in the minority.  You are welcome to your opinion, and free to state it, but it does not change the simple fact of what I was saying, that most Americans support the death penalty and are willing to take the chance of executing the innocent.  <br>
<br>
There is frankly, no other explanation.  We HAVE the death penalty in America.  By your own, (and I will not dispute them) assertions, we have executed innocent people in the past.  Yet the death penalty is still in effect, at least up through Monday.  Therefore, it logically follows that America as a whole agrees it is ok to remotely risk killing an innocent person (and in rare cases actually do it) in order to kill the truly guilty.  We may not like it, and we certainly want to avoid killing innocents, but my point is the representative democracy of America, and all states with death penalty laws, have voted to HAVE the death penalty, which includes the chance of killing innocents.<br>
