<br>
We apply the death penalty rarely and only after a lengthy appeal process, hence it is not a detterent to criminals.<br>
<br>
Now for China.... (not saying I would rather live there mind you!)<br>
<br>
China has a population over 4 times larger than the USA, yet their crime rate is less than 1/10 of ours!  Why is that?<br>
<br>
In the US, if you do something that is not a capital offense, you will most likely spend a few years in prison, then get out.  You can do this several times, hopping in and out of prison, until finally (maybe) a judge deems you not reformable and puts you away for the rest of your life.  We frequently have people who get out of prison, realize that life in prison was BETTER THAN OUTSIDE FOR THEM (!!!!!), so they commint some small infraction so they can get back in.<br>
<br>
China..... you commit a non-capital offense, you will spend 7 years performing hard manual labor, getting 2 meals of rice and water each day.  You get out and perform some other small offense?  See the penalty for Capital offense, as it is the same.<br>
<br>
China's penalty for a capital offense...  You are given ONE trial, with a reasonable chance to defend yourself (with lawyer), and if convicted, you are taken out to the prison yard, made to kneel down, and shot in the back of the head by a soldier.  Your family is then required to collect your corpse for burial, and are given a bill for the cost of the bullet.<br>
<br>
Which system seems to be a better deterrent?<br>
<br>
We in the USA need to take a much firmer stance against crimes, and enforce much more swift and effective penalties, if we ever want to see a reduction in crimes.<br>
<br>
Torturing a criminal, being with them alone for 5 min with a baseball bat, drawing and quartering them (that's the 4 horses thing), etc. are all just demeaning to the people carrying out said punishment.  Just treat them like we do a rabid animal and them move on with life, feeling safer now that a danger to the general populace (and ME and everyone I know are included in that) has been removed.<br>
